Modifications relative to upstream
----------------------------------

1. `programs/pyth-solana-receiver/` — a port of `pyth-solana-receiver`
   from `anchor-lang` `0.32.1` to `anchor-lang` `1.0.1` for use as the
   cf-invariants-pyth harness target. Build-system and dependency
   surfaces were updated to the newer anchor-lang; program logic is
   preserved 1:1 from upstream.

2. `vendor/pyth-solana-receiver-sdk/` — a minimal vendored copy of
   the upstream `pyth_solana_receiver_sdk` crate sufficient to satisfy
   the receiver's compile-time imports (`Config`, `DataSource`,
   `PriceUpdateV2`, `TwapUpdate`, `VerificationLevel`,
   `PostUpdateAtomicParams`, `PostUpdateParams`,
   `PostTwapUpdateParams`, PDA seed constants, program ID).

3. `vendor/pythnet-sdk/` — a minimal vendored copy of upstream
   `pythnet/pythnet_sdk` sufficient to satisfy the receiver's
   compile-time imports (`MerkleRoot`, `Keccak160`, `Message`,
   `TwapMessage`, `from_slice`, `WormholeMessage`, `WormholePayload`,
   `MerklePriceUpdate`).

4. `vendor/wormhole-core-bridge-stub/` — a CaliperForge-authored stub
   crate exposing only the surface the receiver reads from upstream
   `wormhole-core-bridge-solana` (the `GuardianSet` account layout,
   `AccountVariant`, `VaaAccount` deserialize/load, `quorum` helper).
   The receiver does NOT CPI-call wormhole — it reads the GuardianSet
   state and verifies VAA signatures locally — so a type-and-state
   stub is sufficient. Stub source is authored by CaliperForge.

5. `references/pyth_receiver_ref/` — a clean baseline copy of the
   ported receiver program plus Crucible fuzz fixtures. The
   fuzz-fixture sources are CaliperForge-authored harness code, not
   upstream code.

6. `references/pyth_receiver_ref_planted_*/` — CaliperForge-authored
   "planted-bug" variants of the clean reference. Each variant
   introduces a small, deliberate logic regression so the Crucible
   harness can prove the corresponding invariant class fires
   (planted >= 1 violation) while the clean reference holds
   (clean = 0 violations).

